out 1451","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1488":"1488","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1376":"1376","1464":"1464","1485":"1485","1428":"1428","Eye, Suffolk":"Eye, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Ongar, Essex, England":"Ongar, Essex, England","Kenton, Suffolk, England":"Kenton, Suffolk, England","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Baylahm, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Eye, Suffolk, England":"Eye, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Sulyard II was born in 1400, in Eye, Suffolk, England, his father, William Sulyard, was 24 and his mother, Joane Goade, was 22. He married Elizabeth Stratton in 1437. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 21 December 1468, in his hometown, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1400–21 December 1468":"1400–21. detsember 1468","1400–1468":"1400–1468","1410–1464":"1410–1464","1428–1488":"1428–1488","1443–1485":"1443–1485","1451–Female":"1451–Surnud","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1378–1400":"1378–1400","1451":"1451","21 December 1464":"21. detsember 1464","21 December 1468":"21. detsember 1468","1437":"1437","1468":"1468","1400":"1400","ABT 1451":"umbes 1451","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1488":"1488","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1376":"1376","1464":"1464","1485":"1485","1428":"1428","Eye, Suffolk":"Eye, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ongar, Essex, England":"Ongar, Essex, England","Kenton, Suffolk, England":"Kenton, Suffolk, England","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Baylahm, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Eye, Suffolk, England":"Eye, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1400–21 December 1468":"1400–21. joulukuuta 1468","1400–1468":"1400–1468","1410–1464":"1410–1464","1428–1488":"1428–1488","1443–1485":"1443–1485","1451–Female":"1451–Kuollut","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1378–1400":"1378–1400","1451":"1451","21 Decemb